# 📂 **5. Results Folder (VERY IMPORTANT)**

Inside `outputs/` include:





Title:  End-to-End AI System for Crop Intelligence and Traffic Analysis with Agentic Orchestration


1. Introduction

This project presents a unified AI system that integrates computer vision pipelines with an agent-based orchestration framework to solve real-world problems in agriculture and traffic monitoring. The system processes raw imagery from drones, satellites, or cameras and produces structured outputs such as heatmaps, GeoJSON, and analytical reports.

The architecture is designed with a focus on:

Scalability
Modularity
Production readiness
Self-optimization through feedback loops


2. Task 1 — Crop Detection Pipeline
Objective

To detect and analyze crop regions from aerial or satellite imagery.

Approach
Input images are preprocessed (resized, normalized).
A deep learning model is used for crop detection/segmentation.
Outputs include structured crop regions and visual overlays.
Pipeline Steps
Image input
Preprocessing (tiling, normalization)
Model inference
Post-processing
Output generation
Output
Annotated crop images
Structured data (optional GeoJSON)
Results
The model successfully identifies crop areas in given images.
Performance depends on image quality and resolution.


3. Task 2 — Traffic Analysis Pipeline
Objective

To analyze traffic from video streams using object detection and tracking.

Approach
Used YOLO-based object detection for identifying vehicles and pedestrians.
Implemented a simple tracker to maintain object continuity across frames.
Generated density maps and heatmaps.
Pipeline Steps
Video input
Frame extraction
Object detection (cars, buses, trucks, persons)
Tracking
Density estimation
Heatmap generation
Sample Output
Frame detections:
~20–22 objects per frame (cars, buses, trucks)
Heatmap visualization showing traffic density
Results
Successfully processed multiple frames with consistent detections.
Generated traffic density heatmaps.


4. Task 3 — Agentic Orchestration System
Objective

To build an intelligent system that dynamically selects and manages pipelines.

Architecture Components
1. Orchestrator Agent
Routes input to correct pipeline (crop or traffic)
Uses LLM-based decision making with fallback logic
2. QC Agent
Evaluates output quality based on confidence
Triggers re-run if confidence is low
3. Memory Module
Stores previous outputs
Maintains history for drift detection
4. Drift Detection
Detects performance degradation over time
Triggers alerts or retraining
5. Reporting Agent
Generates final structured reports
System Flow
Input received
Orchestrator selects pipeline
Pipeline runs inference
QC evaluates output
Memory stores results
Reporting agent generates output
Key Feature
Fallback logic implemented to handle API failures (e.g., Gemini quota exceeded)
5. Task 4 — System Design & Production Readiness
5.1 Architecture Overview

The system consists of five major layers:

1. Data Ingestion Layer
Sources: satellite, drone, IoT cameras
Storage: cloud object storage
Preprocessing: tiling (512×512), normalization
2. Inference Layer
Models: crop detection, traffic detection
GPU: A100/T4
Batch processing for efficiency
3. Agentic Orchestration Layer
Orchestrator, QC, Memory, Drift Detection
LLM-based routing and fallback
4. Output Layer
GeoJSON
Heatmaps
Dashboards
5. Feedback Loop
Metrics → retraining → improved model
5.2 MLOps & Monitoring Plan
Metrics Monitored
mAP (accuracy)
Latency per tile
Throughput
Confidence scores
Drift score
Alerting System
Low confidence → re-run
Drift detected → alert
Latency spike → scale resources
Retraining Strategy
Triggered by:
Performance drop
Drift detection
Uses versioned datasets
Model Versioning
Managed using MLflow / W&B
Supports rollback and tracking
5.3 Scalability & Cost Analysis
Inference Time
GPU	Time per Tile
A100	~50 ms
T4	~120 ms
Processing 10,000 Tiles/Day
Batch size: 32
Parallel GPUs: 4–8
Total time: < 1 hour (A100 cluster)
Cloud Cost Estimate
A100: ~$50/day
T4: ~$20–30/day
Edge Deployment
Possible with lightweight models
Full processing remains cloud-based
6. Results
Traffic pipeline processed multiple frames successfully
Detected ~20+ objects per frame
Generated heatmaps
Agent system correctly routed tasks
Memory and drift logic executed successfully
7. Limitations
Limited dataset size affects generalization
LLM dependency may cause latency or failures
Real-time performance requires GPU scaling
Tracking is basic (can be improved with advanced trackers like DeepSORT)
8. Conclusion

This project demonstrates a complete AI system integrating multiple pipelines with agent-based orchestration. The system is modular, scalable, and production-ready, with strong support for monitoring and continuous improvement.

Future improvements include:

Advanced tracking algorithms
Better drift detection
Real-time deployment optimization

